And we had hardcore sergeants that work up and, and yeah.

1204
01:51:50.50 --> 01:51:54.74
So we maintain this, which it was enabled by our RCOs.

1205
01:51:54.74 --> 01:51:57.14
Is this really aggressive company for sure.

1206
01:51:57.14 --> 01:52:01.74
And then in order to maintain or establish security,

1207
01:52:02.58 --> 01:52:04.02
you're going out on patrols.

1208
01:52:04.02 --> 01:52:04.86
Yeah.

1209
01:52:04.86 --> 01:52:06.46
You're taking A&A with you all the time?

1210
01:52:08.06 --> 01:52:09.22
Trying not to.

1211
01:52:09.22 --> 01:52:12.32
Initially we would often forget them at the,

1212
01:52:12.32 --> 01:52:16.58
at the patrol base, but towards the latter half

1213
01:52:16.58 --> 01:52:18.38
of the deployment, we were bringing them,

1214
01:52:18.38 --> 01:52:20.74
always bringing them out, but we, we,

1215
01:52:20.74 --> 01:52:23.26
that first mission had like such high visibility

1216
01:52:23.26 --> 01:52:26.30
because it was a, we were scaring battalion objectives

1217
01:52:26.30 --> 01:52:28.82
and doing a three day operation that we had to have

1218
01:52:28.82 --> 01:52:30.50
the A&A with us.

1219
01:52:30.50 --> 01:52:33.46
But they and they were happy to not go out

1220
01:52:33.46 --> 01:52:35.10
and we were happy to not take them out.

1221
01:52:35.10 --> 01:52:38.54
And so it wasn't towards the latter half of the deployment

1222
01:52:38.54 --> 01:52:41.54
that we really started kind of employing them consistently.

1223
01:52:42.94 --> 01:52:47.94
But yeah, those, those first patrols were conventional

1224
01:52:48.98 --> 01:52:49.82
fighting.

1225
01:52:49.82 --> 01:52:51.88
I mean, it was the enemy was in a defense in depth

1226
01:52:51.88 --> 01:52:55.26
with obstacles covered by machine guns.

1227
01:52:55.26 --> 01:52:59.74
And we were on the offense and just straight assaulting

1228
01:52:59.74 --> 01:53:00.90
into an enemy defense.

1229
01:53:00.90 --> 01:53:05.90
And that's, and so anything about improving local security

1230
01:53:06.14 --> 01:53:08.58
or doing any kind of counterinsurgency, it was no,

1231
01:53:08.58 --> 01:53:12.10
just go out there and kill as many guys as you can.

1232
01:53:13.02 --> 01:53:15.82
Yeah. Well, that's actually part of counterinsurgency

1233
01:53:15.82 --> 01:53:17.46
is killing a bunch of bad guys.

1234
01:53:17.46 --> 01:53:21.02
And that was, that's a very effective and necessary part

1235
01:53:21.02 --> 01:53:22.54
of it because you can't build schools

1236
01:53:22.54 --> 01:53:24.14
while you're getting blown up.

1237
01:53:24.14 --> 01:53:27.62
And, you know, security for the populace is the way that I,

1238
01:53:28.98 --> 01:53:31.02
for lack of a better word, pitched it up my chain

1239
01:53:31.02 --> 01:53:32.54
of command, what we were doing.

1240
01:53:32.54 --> 01:53:34.34
Hey, we're going to provide security for the populace.

1241
01:53:34.34 --> 01:53:35.42
Well, how are you going to do that?

1242
01:53:35.42 --> 01:53:36.50
We're going to kill all these bad guys

1243
01:53:36.50 --> 01:53:39.10
or at least as many of them as we can.

1244
01:53:39.10 --> 01:53:41.42
What was your op tempo like?

1245
01:53:41.42 --> 01:53:42.82
So how often are you guys going out?

1246
01:53:42.82 --> 01:53:44.50
How long are you staying out for?

1247
01:53:44.50 --> 01:53:48.98
I mean, every day, I mean, we're doing

1248
01:53:48.98 --> 01:53:52.30
a platoon size patrols every day for the first month or two.

1249
01:53:52.30 --> 01:53:57.30
And that's because you needed a platoon size element

1250
01:53:57.58 --> 01:54:00.58
to get in the, to effectively fight the types of fights

1251
01:54:00.58 --> 01:54:01.74
that we were engaged in.

1252
01:54:01.74 --> 01:54:03.62
And then it, then it was a squad.

1253
01:54:03.62 --> 01:54:06.22
And, but it was tough because you had a,

1254
01:54:06.22 --> 01:54:10.10
you had a squad on post, you had a squad on QRF,

1255
01:54:10.10 --> 01:54:12.10
and then you had a squad patrolling.

1256
01:54:12.10 --> 01:54:16.14
And the QRF squad almost always got called out.

1257
01:54:16.14 --> 01:54:19.18
And so that rest squad was really never resting.

1258
01:54:19.18 --> 01:54:21.62
And so you're either on post patrolling

1259
01:54:21.62 --> 01:54:23.66
or responding out as QRF.

1260
01:54:23.66 --> 01:54:27.10
So it was, it was a, that tempo was pretty brutal.

1261
01:54:27.10 --> 01:54:29.50
And so the troops were out every day.

1262
01:54:32.34 --> 01:54:33.58
I don't know if this is the right word,

1263
01:54:33.58 --> 01:54:35.18
but it sounds like it might be the right word.

1264
01:54:35.18 --> 01:54:37.38
You kind of gotten a little bit of trouble

1265
01:54:37.38 --> 01:54:38.62
up the chain of command.

1266
01:54:38.62 --> 01:54:39.46
Yeah.

1267
01:54:40.38 --> 01:54:43.34
You got counseled for your cowboy attitude

1268
01:54:43.34 --> 01:54:44.18
and this kind of thing.

1269
01:54:44.18 --> 01:54:45.02
Break that down a little bit.

1270
01:54:45.02 --> 01:54:46.50
What mistakes did you make?

1271
01:54:46.50 --> 01:54:48.46
What could you have done that better?

1272
01:54:48.46 --> 01:54:49.30
Where were you right?

1273
01:54:49.30 --> 01:54:50.30
Where were you wrong?

1274
01:54:52.78 --> 01:54:56.66
We were out on operation and we'd been out until two or three

1275
01:54:56.66 --> 01:55:00.70
and I, and I called into the main, the CP.

1276
01:55:00.70 --> 01:55:02.58
And I said, hey, we're gonna, we're gonna turn our radio

1277
01:55:02.58 --> 01:55:03.42
off for a couple hours.

1278
01:55:03.42 --> 01:55:05.10
Conserve battery will be up at zero six

1279
01:55:05.10 --> 01:55:07.18
and call them with the radio check.

1280
01:55:07.18 --> 01:55:09.18
And when I turned the radio back on at zero six

1281
01:55:09.18 --> 01:55:10.78
couple hours later, it was like,

1282
01:55:10.78 --> 01:55:13.22
broken arrow, where are you sledgehammer?

1283
01:55:13.22 --> 01:55:14.94
Have you been overrun?

1284
01:55:14.94 --> 01:55:16.38
Sledgehammer one, call in.

1285
01:55:16.38 --> 01:55:21.14
I'm like, hey, we called you guys, got Roger up

1286
01:55:21.14 --> 01:55:23.42
that we were turning the radio off

1287
01:55:23.42 --> 01:55:26.98
and the night watcher said that was good to go.

1288
01:55:27.78 --> 01:55:30.30
So, and it's like, no, you're not in the log book.

1289
01:55:30.30 --> 01:55:35.30
I'm like, so yeah, when we got back,

1290
01:55:35.30 --> 01:55:38.22
you know, my CO was there and he said,

1291
01:55:38.22 --> 01:55:39.90
you know, I'm gonna kick your ass

1292
01:55:39.90 --> 01:55:41.58
and you think you don't have to call in

1293
01:55:41.58 --> 01:55:43.22
and you don't think you don't have to report.

1294
01:55:43.22 --> 01:55:47.02
And one of my squad leaders, we were in a fight

1295
01:55:47.02 --> 01:55:49.94
and they had shot some already or a high mar.

1296
01:55:49.94 --> 01:55:52.78
And the main kept calling for a sit-rep.

1297
01:55:52.78 --> 01:55:53.94
And you know, what's the BDA?

1298
01:55:53.94 --> 01:55:54.78
What's the sit-rep?

1299
01:55:54.78 --> 01:55:56.82
And he said, how about you guys just grab a cup of coffee,

1300
01:55:56.82 --> 01:55:58.18
take a seat, I'm in a fight.

1301
01:55:59.18 --> 01:56:04.02
And you know, we had this company gunny Carlisle.

1302
01:56:04.02 --> 01:56:06.38
He was a savage dude and he's like,

1303
01:56:06.38 --> 01:56:08.18
what'd you say you motherfucker?

1304
01:56:08.18 --> 01:56:10.26
Like they're fighting over the radio.

1305
01:56:10.26 --> 01:56:12.58
So my guys were, yeah, my guys were,

1306
01:56:14.50 --> 01:56:16.58
it's like kind of that common tension

1307
01:56:16.58 --> 01:56:19.94
between higher headquarters and the dudes doing the fighting.

1308
01:56:19.94 --> 01:56:24.62
And so yeah, we got reigned in and we got,

1309
01:56:24.62 --> 01:56:26.62
but you know, it was punishment

1310
01:56:26.62 --> 01:56:29.46
that had to go back to the company position

1311
01:56:29.46 --> 01:56:31.30
from being out at a patrol base,

1312
01:56:31.30 --> 01:56:33.50
just as the platoon by ourselves.

1313
01:56:33.50 --> 01:56:36.66
But it wouldn't, it turned out it was a reward

1314
01:56:36.66 --> 01:56:40.26
because the area around the company

1315
01:56:40.26 --> 01:56:42.78
hadn't been patrolled aggressively.

1316
01:56:42.78 --> 01:56:44.94
And we had been patrolling now for a month, month and a half.

1317
01:56:44.94 --> 01:56:46.58
So we kind of created a little security bubble.

1318
01:56:46.58 --> 01:56:48.58
We were having a harder time getting into fights.

1319
01:56:48.58 --> 01:56:49.66
And so they brought us back.

1320
01:56:49.66 --> 01:56:50.86
And then the first time we go out,

1321
01:56:50.86 --> 01:56:53.50
we killed a ton of dudes and come back with some AK-47s.

1322
01:56:53.50 --> 01:56:55.74
We're like, yeah, such hammer once here now.

1323
01:56:55.74 --> 01:56:57.10
You know, here's his AKs.

1324
01:56:58.10 --> 01:57:02.38
And so yeah, I could have had more tacked for sure.

1325
01:57:03.90 --> 01:57:06.50
Yeah, I was probably light on tacked.

1326
01:57:06.50 --> 01:57:09.94
You know, one thing I used to tell my guys was that,

1327
01:57:09.94 --> 01:57:13.30
like the next echelon is always messed up, right?

1328
01:57:13.30 --> 01:57:15.66
From our perspective, the next echelon up the chain of command

1329
01:57:15.66 --> 01:57:17.46
is always like, they don't understand.

1330
01:57:17.46 --> 01:57:18.30
Well, here's the deal.

1331
01:57:18.30 --> 01:57:19.14
Why don't they understand?

1332
01:57:19.14 --> 01:57:19.98
They don't understand

1333
01:57:19.98 --> 01:57:22.14
because I'm not doing a good job of pushing them information.

1334
01:57:22.14 --> 01:57:24.30
And I'm not seeing what their perspective is

1335
01:57:24.30 --> 01:57:26.18
because they're probably got someone screaming at them,

1336
01:57:26.18 --> 01:57:28.02
going, what do you mean you're dropping already into that?

1337
01:57:28.02 --> 01:57:29.18
Well, you tell us what's going on.

1338
01:57:29.18 --> 01:57:32.26
And they're asking, and that's how these things,

1339
01:57:32.26 --> 01:57:33.58
that's how you get a little disconnect.

1340
01:57:33.58 --> 01:57:36.38
You get a disconnect between the guys that are fighting

1341
01:57:36.38 --> 01:57:38.18
and the guys that are not.

1342
01:57:38.18 --> 01:57:40.58
There can be some animosity there

1343
01:57:40.58 --> 01:57:41.50
and it can be a problem.

1344
01:57:41.50 --> 01:57:42.42
If you're not careful,

1345
01:57:42.42 --> 01:57:44.14
especially from a leadership position,

1346
01:57:44.14 --> 01:57:46.82
you know, for you guys that are out there,

1347
01:57:46.82 --> 01:57:49.66
you're gonna be the one that translates things

1348
01:57:49.66 --> 01:57:51.58
up and down the chain of command.

1349
01:57:51.58 --> 01:57:54.82
And that is not an easy job,

1350
01:57:54.82 --> 01:57:56.38
but it's a really important job

1351
01:57:56.38 --> 01:57:58.66
because if we have a real disconnect,

1352
01:57:58.66 --> 01:58:00.70
then we're not getting the support that we need

1353
01:58:00.70 --> 01:58:02.86
and it causes all kinds of problems.

1354
01:58:02.86 --> 01:58:07.78
So don't take anything personally, right?

1355
01:58:07.78 --> 01:58:10.86
When they're asking you what the hell's going on,

1356
01:58:10.86 --> 01:58:12.22
just do your best to try and tell them

1357
01:58:12.22 --> 01:58:13.42
what the hell's going on.

1358
01:58:13.42 --> 01:58:17.46
When they're asking you stupid questions,

1359
01:58:18.46 --> 01:58:19.98
it's because you didn't tell them,

1360
01:58:19.98 --> 01:58:23.10
well, you know, how you were going to do a Kazovac

1361
01:58:23.10 --> 01:58:24.42
in this particular scenario

1362
01:58:24.42 --> 01:58:28.70
or how you were gonna handle this particular type of threat.

1363
01:58:28.70 --> 01:58:29.82
They're asking you this stuff

1364
01:58:29.82 --> 01:58:30.66
because they wanna know,

1365
01:58:30.66 --> 01:58:33.94
because you didn't tell them and just do your best.

1366
01:58:33.94 --> 01:58:35.54
I know it's hard.

1367
01:58:35.54 --> 01:58:37.94
And for senior leaders out there,

1368
01:58:37.94 --> 01:58:39.94
when your folks are in the field,

1369
01:58:39.94 --> 01:58:42.18
they're working on some shit.

1370
01:58:42.18 --> 01:58:44.02
And as soon as they get the chance,

1371
01:58:44.02 --> 01:58:45.58
they're gonna tell you what's up,

1372
01:58:45.58 --> 01:58:49.06
but leave them alone as long as you possibly can,

1373
01:58:49.06 --> 01:58:52.54
leave them alone and let them sort their shit out

1374
01:58:52.54 --> 01:58:53.74
and then they'll get back to you

1375
01:58:53.74 --> 01:58:56.46
and you can get your numbers and get your update

1376
01:58:56.46 --> 01:58:58.74
and get your sit-rep and all that.

1377
01:58:58.74 --> 01:59:00.98
Just try and understand each other's perspectives,

1378
01:59:00.98 --> 01:59:02.66
please, it goes a long way.

1379
01:59:02.66 --> 01:59:06.58
Yeah, I think that was a good summation of lessons learned.

1380
01:59:10.66 --> 01:59:12.62
All this fighting going on,

1381
01:59:13.54 --> 01:59:15.42
there's gonna be a price.

1382
01:59:15.42 --> 01:59:19.38
Cam, your buddy Cam gets severely wounded by an IED.

1383
01:59:20.58 --> 01:59:25.58
Lost his right leg, injured his left leg.

1384
01:59:26.34 --> 01:59:27.78
Or sorry, lost one leg.

1385
01:59:27.78 --> 01:59:29.98
It really injured the other one.

1386
01:59:29.98 --> 01:59:32.02
Bright eyes messed up.

1387
01:59:32.02 --> 01:59:34.34
That seemed, at least when I read it in the book,

1388
01:59:34.34 --> 01:59:37.06
it seemed like that was a little bit

1389
01:59:37.06 --> 01:59:39.34
of a reality check for you

1390
01:59:40.22 --> 01:59:44.22
because we are young and we feel invincible.

1391
01:59:45.54 --> 01:59:48.02
Yeah, Cam was this kind of larger than life.

1392
01:59:48.02 --> 01:59:52.10
John Wayne kind of figured to me a guy, big, strong dude

1393
01:59:52.10 --> 01:59:54.94
that we all looked up to, charismatic.

1394
01:59:54.94 --> 01:59:58.86
And when I came into patrol base that day,

1395
01:59:58.86 --> 02:00:00.94
Will Donnelly, the second platoon commander,

1396
02:00:00.94 --> 02:00:04.30
meets me and says, I don't think Cam's gonna make it.

1397
02:00:04.30 --> 02:00:08.06
And we were taking casualties at such a crazy rate.

1398
02:00:08.06 --> 02:00:11.14
And I'm like, man, if Cam can go down, I mean, like,

1399
02:00:13.10 --> 02:00:15.98
and I hadn't, I was good in a firefight,

1400
02:00:15.98 --> 02:00:19.06
I could still kind of compartmentalize and focus on

1401
02:00:19.06 --> 02:00:21.10
the thing that I needed to focus on in that moment

1402
02:00:21.10 --> 02:00:23.24
to make the right decisions.

1403
02:00:23.24 --> 02:00:28.24
But I was, I, there's another great scene in Gates of Fire

1404
02:00:30.000 --> 02:00:33.88
where the Spartans before battle will break the twigs

1405
02:00:33.88 --> 02:00:36.08
and they'll put half the twig in the basket.

1406
02:00:36.08 --> 02:00:40.28
It's like symbolic of a dog tag.

1407
02:00:40.28 --> 02:00:42.000
And so that if they get so disfigured,

1408
02:00:42.000 --> 02:00:44.36
they match up the twigs at the end of the battle

1409
02:00:44.36 --> 02:00:46.000
and they say, okay, this is this guy.

1410
02:00:46.000 --> 02:00:47.48
But there's another aspect of that.

1411
02:00:47.48 --> 02:00:50.04
It's they break off their humanity

1412
02:00:50.04 --> 02:00:53.32
because their sons or dads or their husbands

1413
02:00:53.32 --> 02:00:55.68
and they're about to go have to stick a zyphosword

1414
02:00:55.68 --> 02:00:56.60
into somebody's guts.

1415
02:00:56.60 --> 02:00:58.56
And so they've got to separate.

1416
02:00:58.56 --> 02:01:02.52
And I still had not separated my humanity

1417
02:01:02.52 --> 02:01:07.12
from the violent warrior killing and death

1418
02:01:07.12 --> 02:01:09.08
that I was so intimately.

1419
02:01:09.08 --> 02:01:10.44
That was the world I was living in.

1420
02:01:10.44 --> 02:01:11.60
I think of like, if you think of it,

1421
02:01:11.60 --> 02:01:14.04
it gets like the river sticks, you know,

1422
02:01:14.04 --> 02:01:16.72
we had crossed the river sticks and we're living in Hades.

1423
02:01:16.72 --> 02:01:19.24
And I kind of had one foot on one shore

1424
02:01:19.24 --> 02:01:20.68
and one foot in hell.

1425
02:01:20.68 --> 02:01:25.68
And I was kind of just, and when I found out,

1426
02:01:26.28 --> 02:01:28.68
when I heard Cannes wasn't gonna make it,

1427
02:01:28.68 --> 02:01:29.64
he did ultimately make it.

1428
02:01:29.64 --> 02:01:33.56
But when I found that out, I just, I broke down.

1429
02:01:33.56 --> 02:01:36.80
And then I went back to my room

1430
02:01:36.80 --> 02:01:40.24
and I had stored away a little Snickers bar

1431
02:01:40.24 --> 02:01:42.04
at the bottom of my ruck.

1432
02:01:42.04 --> 02:01:44.04
And I thought, on a rainy day,

1433
02:01:44.04 --> 02:01:45.56
you will need this for your morale.

1434
02:01:45.56 --> 02:01:47.92
And I didn't think that rainy day was gonna be like

1435
02:01:47.92 --> 02:01:49.36
a weekend to happen to the deployment,

1436
02:01:49.36 --> 02:01:52.72
but I go to dig in my ruck and I find that

1437
02:01:52.72 --> 02:01:55.28
these little tailband mice have been living

1438
02:01:55.28 --> 02:01:58.60
and shitting in my ruck and they ate my Snickers bar.

1439
02:01:58.60 --> 02:02:01.68
And I had no more resilience left, you know?

1440
02:02:01.68 --> 02:02:05.88
And so that was like the, and so I got sick.

1441
02:02:05.88 --> 02:02:07.48
I was puke and emotional.

1442
02:02:07.48 --> 02:02:09.76
Not in front of my troops, this was all private,

1443
02:02:09.76 --> 02:02:12.88
but it was at that point that I said,

1444
02:02:12.88 --> 02:02:16.44
you can't be feeling these things anymore.

1445
02:02:16.44 --> 02:02:20.60
Like you have a job and so you separate

1446
02:02:20.60 --> 02:02:23.44
from, you detach from that humanity

1447
02:02:23.44 --> 02:02:26.76
and everything is compartmentalized from that moment forward,

1448
02:02:26.76 --> 02:02:30.56
which makes you super effective under fire.

1449
02:02:30.56 --> 02:02:33.72
The issue is if you don't reconnect to that humanity

1450
02:02:33.72 --> 02:02:38.28
after your deployment, you become cold,

1451
02:02:38.28 --> 02:02:40.56
emotionally unavailable.

1452
02:02:40.56 --> 02:02:44.48
You don't experience the richness and fullness of life.

1453
02:02:44.48 --> 02:02:47.44
It's a really safe way to live, very compartmentalized

1454
02:02:47.44 --> 02:02:49.84
because I don't get too happy, I don't get too sad,

1455
02:02:50.84 --> 02:02:54.52
but it's not a very fulfilling way to live.

1456
02:02:54.52 --> 02:02:57.12
And the longer you, and you know,

1457
02:02:57.12 --> 02:02:59.000
I was right back in Afghanistan 12 months later.

1458
02:02:59.000 --> 02:03:03.16
And so the longer you kind of keep all those nerve endings

1459
02:03:03.16 --> 02:03:05.60
dead so that you don't can't feel anything,

1460
02:03:05.60 --> 02:03:07.76
longer is harder to turn them back on.

1461
02:03:07.76 --> 02:03:12.76
And also you start to get afraid of like,

1462
02:03:12.76 --> 02:03:17.24
what will I feel when I do turn all that stuff back on?

1463
02:03:17.24 --> 02:03:18.72
Because I've been packing stuff in the sea bag

1464
02:03:18.72 --> 02:03:20.72
for a long time here.

1465
02:03:20.72 --> 02:03:23.24
And so what I convinced myself is,

1466
02:03:23.24 --> 02:03:25.64
is that like, hey, you don't have time.

1467
02:03:25.64 --> 02:03:27.52
You got troops to lead, you got stuff to do,

1468
02:03:27.52 --> 02:03:30.88
like you don't have, and what really what I found is like,

1469
02:03:30.88 --> 02:03:34.000
I didn't have the courage to turn them back on.

1470
02:03:34.000 --> 02:03:35.32
I didn't have the courage to feel the things

1471
02:03:35.32 --> 02:03:36.64
that I needed to feel to figure out

1472
02:03:36.64 --> 02:03:38.20
what the hell was going on.

1473
02:03:38.20 --> 02:03:41.08
And I basically told myself a lie that said,

1474
02:03:41.08 --> 02:03:42.16
you're too busy, you're too busy,

1475
02:03:42.16 --> 02:03:44.40
but really I was too scared to unpack that sea bag.

1476
02:03:44.40 --> 02:03:48.16
And as I said, good way to be in combat,

1477
02:03:48.16 --> 02:03:49.52
probably a bad way to live.

1478
02:03:50.48 --> 02:03:52.16
Well, I think it's important to,

1479
02:03:52.16 --> 02:03:53.96
a lot of times things are going on around us

1480
02:03:53.96 --> 02:03:55.32
and we just don't know what they're happening.

1481
02:03:55.32 --> 02:03:57.96
So like you pointing that out,

1482
02:03:57.96 --> 02:03:59.48
it will help someone else go,

1483
02:03:59.48 --> 02:04:00.40
oh, I know what's going on.

1484
02:04:00.40 --> 02:04:03.72
Like I know my wife, I was on deployment,

1485
02:04:03.72 --> 02:04:05.36
my wife sent me an email.

1486
02:04:05.36 --> 02:04:07.72
This is before FaceTime and stuff like this,

1487
02:04:07.72 --> 02:04:10.000
but she sent me an email and said,

1488
02:04:10.000 --> 02:04:13.04
the kids wanna see a picture of where you sleep.

1489
02:04:13.04 --> 02:04:15.36
Like, can you send a picture of where you sleep?

1490
02:04:15.36 --> 02:04:17.84
And I said, yep, got it.

1491
02:04:17.84 --> 02:04:20.76
And I remember I took a picture of,

1492
02:04:20.76 --> 02:04:24.44
like my little wooden plywood cot thing.

1493
02:04:24.44 --> 02:04:26.64
And I looked at it and I was like, oh, this isn't good.

1494
02:04:26.64 --> 02:04:31.64
And I pulled out from some dug down in some backpack,

1495
02:04:32.40 --> 02:04:34.40
grabbed some pictures of my wife and kids,

1496
02:04:34.40 --> 02:04:38.22
hung them up around the bed, took a picture,

1497
02:04:38.22 --> 02:04:41.74
took them back down, put them back in the folder

1498
02:04:41.74 --> 02:04:44.78
and back in the rucksack because the last thing

1499
02:04:44.78 --> 02:04:47.62
I needed to be doing was thinking about my wife and kids

1500
02:04:47.62 --> 02:04:49.98
when I got guys that are, you know,

1501
02:04:49.98 --> 02:04:52.46
counting on me to make decisions.

1502
02:04:53.90 --> 02:04:58.18
And I think that that was like a physical representation

1503
02:04:58.18 --> 02:05:00.46
that I knew what I was doing.

1504
02:05:00.46 --> 02:05:02.82
And I think that when I got home, I kind of knew,

1505
02:05:02.82 --> 02:05:05.94
okay, you can put these pictures back up now in your head.

1506
02:05:05.94 --> 02:05:07.34
And I think a lot of times,

1507
02:05:07.34 --> 02:05:09.38
like just you, the way you're describing that,

1508
02:05:09.38 --> 02:05:14.02
other people will recognize that,

1509
02:05:14.02 --> 02:05:15.58
oh, they took those pictures down.

1510
02:05:15.58 --> 02:05:17.82
They put them in a folder, they're not looking at them.

1511
02:05:17.82 --> 02:05:19.34
When you get done with that deployment,

1512
02:05:19.34 --> 02:05:22.34
you can open that folder back up and it's gonna be okay.

1513
02:05:23.82 --> 02:05:25.10
Important stuff to learn.

1514
02:05:27.10 --> 02:05:30.02
At this point, you meet Zach for the first time.

1515
02:05:30.02 --> 02:05:31.62
Seemed like you guys kicked it off pretty good,

1516
02:05:31.62 --> 02:05:33.58
hit it off pretty good right out of the gate.

1517
02:05:33.58 --> 02:05:37.54
Initially very transactional, he was a good interpreter.

1518
02:05:37.54 --> 02:05:39.98
He knew his past due, he knew English.

1519
02:05:39.98 --> 02:05:43.50
Up to that point, the only interpreters who were left

1520
02:05:43.50 --> 02:05:46.06
either didn't speak English or didn't speak the local dialect.

1521
02:05:46.06 --> 02:05:47.70
And so they knew they weren't gonna be able to get a job,

1522
02:05:47.70 --> 02:05:48.54
so they hung around.

1523
02:05:48.54 --> 02:05:52.66
And what I was finding is that every interpreter was quitting

1524
02:05:53.70 --> 02:05:57.42
or they were such a liability under fire

1525
02:05:57.42 --> 02:06:00.06
that we'd have bounded a couple hundred meters,

1526
02:06:00.06 --> 02:06:03.06
like where's the term and we gotta go.

1527
02:06:03.06 --> 02:06:08.06
And so we had had a rough, rough go with our interpreter.

1528
02:06:08.06 --> 02:06:10.78
So yeah, he shows up, he's fit, he's healthy,

1529
02:06:10.78 --> 02:06:13.14
he's not a coward and yeah, that's good.

1530
02:06:15.06 --> 02:06:17.42
Meanwhile, you're pushing, going to the book here.

1531
02:06:18.42 --> 02:06:20.34
In our first nine days of operations,

1532
02:06:20.34 --> 02:06:22.66
First Platoon had killed 15 Taliban.

1533
02:06:22.66 --> 02:06:24.54
We were fighting harder and killing more enemy

1534
02:06:24.54 --> 02:06:26.26
than any unit in three five.

1535
02:06:26.26 --> 02:06:27.98
By extension, that meant we were fighting

1536
02:06:27.98 --> 02:06:31.06
and killing more than any unit in Afghanistan.

1537
02:06:31.06 --> 02:06:33.90
I saw that as in keeping with my CO's direction

1538
02:06:33.90 --> 02:06:35.54
as I understood it.

1539
02:06:35.54 --> 02:06:37.90
But pushing that hard can create political

1540
02:06:37.90 --> 02:06:40.78
and personal issues that people more removed

1541
02:06:40.78 --> 02:06:43.30
from the sharp end of things can perceive

1542
02:06:43.30 --> 02:06:45.30
as unnecessary risk.

1543
02:06:45.30 --> 02:06:47.58
They may even be right, given the clarity

1544
02:06:47.58 --> 02:06:49.30
that distance can offer.

1545
02:06:49.30 --> 02:06:52.10
In my aggressive approach to the area of operations,

1546
02:06:52.10 --> 02:06:53.86
I followed the rules of engagement,

1547
02:06:53.86 --> 02:06:56.94
but I was not particularly attuned to political liability

1548
02:06:56.94 --> 02:07:00.50
that increased the farther anyone got from PB fires.

1549
02:07:00.50 --> 02:07:04.18
But I was consciously absorbing a lot of physical risk.

1550
02:07:04.18 --> 02:07:05.90
It made me short of patience with people

1551
02:07:05.90 --> 02:07:08.70
I saw as less engaged, which to be honest,

1552
02:07:08.70 --> 02:07:10.38
was everyone who was in Afghanistan

1553
02:07:10.38 --> 02:07:12.66
and not in First Platoon.

1554
02:07:12.66 --> 02:07:14.62
When I got back to PB fires that day,

1555
02:07:14.62 --> 02:07:16.82
the CO told me he was pulling First Platoon back

1556
02:07:16.82 --> 02:07:18.78
to Fobb, increment over his concerns

1557
02:07:18.78 --> 02:07:22.02
that I required closer supervision.

1558
02:07:22.02 --> 02:07:24.58
We were moving, but thankfully,

1559
02:07:24.58 --> 02:07:26.02
Zach was coming with us.

1560
02:07:26.02 --> 02:07:31.02
We kind of addressed that,

1561
02:07:32.42 --> 02:07:35.58
the fact that that little disconnect showed up

1562
02:07:36.98 --> 02:07:39.94
between you and this is like,

1563
02:07:39.94 --> 02:07:41.94
I mean, how many books can you read,

1564
02:07:41.94 --> 02:07:44.94
movies can you watch about that disconnect

1565
02:07:44.94 --> 02:07:48.46
between the remps, the rear echelon motherfuckers

1566
02:07:48.46 --> 02:07:50.50
and the people on the front line?

1567
02:07:50.50 --> 02:07:56.94
There's a lot of documentation about that.

1568
02:07:57.94 --> 02:08:01.98
You just, you get back to Fobb, increment, like you said,

1569
02:08:01.98 --> 02:08:06.14
and the ops continue.

1570
02:08:06.14 --> 02:08:08.14
The ops are still going on.

1571
02:08:08.14 --> 02:08:09.46
Back to the book.

1572
02:08:09.46 --> 02:08:13.66
That command is a lonely, is a trite observation,

1573
02:08:13.66 --> 02:08:16.78
but it is no less true for the countless times

1574
02:08:16.78 --> 02:08:18.02
it's been observed.

1575
02:08:18.02 --> 02:08:19.46
It should be paired with the fact

1576
02:08:19.46 --> 02:08:20.94
that leadership hurts.

1577
02:08:20.94 --> 02:08:23.22
Every time you discipline a Marine that you love,

1578
02:08:23.22 --> 02:08:24.82
every time you watch them bleed,

1579
02:08:24.82 --> 02:08:29.42
every time you watch them breathe their last, it hurts.

1580
02:08:29.42 --> 02:08:31.90
I was 24 years old and living a reality

1581
02:08:31.90 --> 02:08:34.34
that I now look back upon and wonder

1582
02:08:34.34 --> 02:08:37.94
if some of it even truly happened.

1583
02:08:37.94 --> 02:08:40.62
I want to deny that humans could be so callous

1584
02:08:40.62 --> 02:08:43.78
as I became in the destruction of people put on this earth

1585
02:08:43.78 --> 02:08:45.94
by the same God I was.

1586
02:08:45.94 --> 02:08:49.38
I was convinced I would not survive Sengen,

1587
02:08:49.38 --> 02:08:52.26
but I had realized that life is a gift

1588
02:08:52.26 --> 02:08:56.42
and if I did survive, I had some growing up to do.

1589
02:08:56.42 --> 02:08:59.42
I prayed to God and asked that if I did survive,

1590
02:08:59.42 --> 02:09:02.06
he would help me live a grateful, meaningful life

1591
02:09:02.06 --> 02:09:04.70
that would do honor to the people denied that chance.

1592
02:09:04.70 --> 02:09:08.62
I was largely incapable of making any objective decisions

1593
02:09:08.62 --> 02:09:10.98
myself beyond where to patrol next

1594
02:09:10.98 --> 02:09:12.82
and how to fight through the next ambush,

1595
02:09:12.82 --> 02:09:17.46
but I was ready to acknowledge I was not the man

1596
02:09:17.46 --> 02:09:18.62
I professed to be.

1597
02:09:19.58 --> 02:09:22.58
I called Andrea and told her I wanted to be a better man

1598
02:09:22.58 --> 02:09:27.58
that I could only do that with her beside me.

1599
02:09:28.26 --> 02:09:30.86
I apologized for mistreating the woman who loved me

1600
02:09:30.86 --> 02:09:32.94
and begged her to take me back.

1601
02:09:32.94 --> 02:09:34.42
She agreed.

1602
02:09:34.42 --> 02:09:37.18
Though I still thought it unlikely I would ever live

1603
02:09:37.18 --> 02:09:42.74
to see her again, the idea was something to live for.

1604
02:09:43.38 --> 02:09:47.14
At some point that evening, the CO came in and told me

1605
02:09:47.14 --> 02:09:49.78
that my friend and mentor, Lieutenant Robert Kelly,

1606
02:09:49.78 --> 02:09:52.78
was dead, struck and killed instantly

1607
02:09:52.78 --> 02:09:54.94
by an IED earlier that day.

1608
02:09:56.74 --> 02:09:59.70
I rolled over and stared at the wall.

1609
02:09:59.70 --> 02:10:03.46
I thought about Rob, Cam West, and me spending the last day

1610
02:10:03.46 --> 02:10:05.78
before we deployed drinking beer at Del Mar

1611
02:10:05.78 --> 02:10:07.26
with Robert and his family.

1612
02:10:10.10 --> 02:10:12.70
The next day was the 245th birthday

1613
02:10:12.70 --> 02:10:14.30
of the United States Marine Corps.

1614
02:10:15.14 --> 02:10:17.30
First platoon killed four Taliban.

1615
02:10:18.98 --> 02:10:20.50
It didn't bring anyone back.

1616
02:10:25.50 --> 02:10:29.78
By Thanksgiving 2010, most of my closest friends in 3.5,

1617
02:10:29.78 --> 02:10:31.90
Rob, Kelly, Cam West, Will Donnelly

1618
02:10:31.90 --> 02:10:36.10
and Gunnery Sergeant Carlisle had been killed or wounded.

1619
02:10:36.10 --> 02:10:39.26
Only Staff Sergeant Henley and Lieutenant Vic Garcia

1620
02:10:39.26 --> 02:10:42.18
who replaced Cam at PB Fires with 3rd platoon remained.

1621
02:10:43.54 --> 02:10:45.78
I only saw Vic in passing.

1622
02:10:45.78 --> 02:10:48.58
Another IOC classmate, James Biler,

1623
02:10:48.58 --> 02:10:51.66
had been horribly wounded, losing both his legs.

1624
02:10:53.50 --> 02:10:55.38
The death or grievous injury of friends

1625
02:10:55.38 --> 02:10:57.30
with whom I had been living, training and fighting

1626
02:10:57.30 --> 02:10:59.94
for two years left me feeling dead inside.

1627
02:10:59.94 --> 02:11:03.98
I was just waiting for my body to catch up.

1628
02:11:05.94 --> 02:11:09.22
We'd arrived in Sengen in October 2010

1629
02:11:09.22 --> 02:11:11.90
and settled into a life of brutal sameness.

1630
02:11:11.90 --> 02:11:15.34
We patrolled through suffocating heat and penetrating cold,

1631
02:11:15.34 --> 02:11:18.54
sometimes multiple hour long patrols in a day.

1632
02:11:18.54 --> 02:11:20.10
We engaged the elders.

1633
02:11:20.10 --> 02:11:21.98
We did post-blast analysis.

1634
02:11:21.98 --> 02:11:23.34
We responded to ambushes.

1635
02:11:23.34 --> 02:11:24.34
We called in medivacs.

1636
02:11:24.34 --> 02:11:25.62
We called in air support.

1637
02:11:25.62 --> 02:11:31.30
We zipped our friends into bags for a final ride home.

1638
02:11:31.30 --> 02:11:33.42
They were men I loved because I knew them

1639
02:11:33.42 --> 02:11:36.34
or I loved despite not knowing them for the simple fact

1640
02:11:36.34 --> 02:11:39.54
that they had volunteered to serve as Marine infantry men

1641
02:11:39.54 --> 02:11:41.10
in a time when that meant war.

1642
02:11:44.02 --> 02:11:46.38
But it was harder and harder to feel that emotion

1643
02:11:46.38 --> 02:11:48.54
as the toll of dead and wounded grew

1644
02:11:48.54 --> 02:11:55.98
and I felt increasingly ground under the wheels of war.

1645
02:11:55.98 --> 02:12:09.26
So this is the burden of command that you're talking about.

1646
02:12:09.26 --> 02:12:13.02
And as you mentioned, it's a burden that leaders

1647
02:12:13.02 --> 02:12:20.42
have to bear alone.

1648
02:12:20.42 --> 02:12:22.70
And what's interesting and it's an interesting,

1649
02:12:22.70 --> 02:12:25.10
I mean, this is what the book is about,

1650
02:12:25.10 --> 02:12:30.94
is that you actually had an outlet for this.

1651
02:12:30.94 --> 02:12:38.70
And that outlet ended up being your interpreter, Zach.

1652
02:12:38.70 --> 02:12:40.66
He wasn't a Marine.

1653
02:12:40.66 --> 02:12:46.38
He was, there was no mask to put on with Zach.

1654
02:12:49.02 --> 02:12:52.86
How did that relationship grow and develop?

1655
02:12:52.86 --> 02:12:58.10
Out of necessity for my sanity is kind of how it came to be.

1656
02:12:58.10 --> 02:13:04.30
And this idea that war is both heaven and hell

1657
02:13:04.30 --> 02:13:08.50
and that each day you're experiencing

1658
02:13:08.50 --> 02:13:11.98
the worst depravity that you can imagine.

1659
02:13:11.98 --> 02:13:15.42
But then you're seeing no greater love

1660
02:13:15.42 --> 02:13:17.70
that has a man who laid down his life for his friends.

1661
02:13:17.70 --> 02:13:22.06
You're seeing the greatest forms of love manifested

1662
02:13:22.06 --> 02:13:25.18
where someone willingly lays down their life for their friend.

1663
02:13:25.18 --> 02:13:29.38
And so you get these little glimpses of heaven and hell.

1664
02:13:29.38 --> 02:13:33.34
And through that, you start to grow and mature.

1665
02:13:33.34 --> 02:13:36.70
And General Madness kind of talks about it.

1666
02:13:36.70 --> 02:13:42.38
He got his PhD in combat, that you learn so much about life

1667
02:13:42.38 --> 02:13:45.62
in five minutes in a firefight that maybe could take

1668
02:13:45.62 --> 02:13:46.98
five years outside of it.

1669
02:13:46.98 --> 02:13:50.86
And so I'm refining my character.

1670
02:13:50.86 --> 02:13:52.18
I'm growing up finally.

1671
02:13:52.18 --> 02:13:53.30
I was a little boy.

1672
02:13:53.30 --> 02:13:55.06
And I went to the combat a little boy.

1673
02:13:55.06 --> 02:13:58.50
And I finally start to say, it's time for you to be a man.

1674
02:13:58.50 --> 02:14:01.90
And none of this is guaranteed.

1675
02:14:01.90 --> 02:14:05.22
And if you do make it, what are you going to do differently?

1676
02:14:05.22 --> 02:14:09.50
Because what you profess is not congruent with your actions.

1677
02:14:09.50 --> 02:14:12.02
And so first time I get the sat phone,

1678
02:14:12.02 --> 02:14:15.14
I call Andrew a little cry and a little sad.

1679
02:14:15.14 --> 02:14:16.22
I know I broke up with you.

1680
02:14:16.22 --> 02:14:17.74
Please forgive me.

1681
02:14:17.74 --> 02:14:18.54
Take me back.

1682
02:14:21.46 --> 02:14:27.38
And then you kind of hinted at this idea

1683
02:14:27.38 --> 02:14:31.70
that as the junior officer, you are the dam.

1684
02:14:31.70 --> 02:14:37.30
You're between two rushing tides, higher, and then

1685
02:14:37.30 --> 02:14:39.10
your troops and your subordinates.

1686
02:14:39.10 --> 02:14:42.10
And so you are in the middle of this.

1687
02:14:42.10 --> 02:14:46.70
And so you're trying to keep all the crap from rolling down

1688
02:14:46.70 --> 02:14:47.30
hill on them.

1689
02:14:47.30 --> 02:14:49.26
But at the same time, you've got all this stuff bubbling up,

1690
02:14:49.26 --> 02:14:51.06
because you've got a bunch of 18-year-old kids that

1691
02:14:51.06 --> 02:14:53.54
got stuff going on in the lives that are losing their own friends.

1692
02:14:53.54 --> 02:14:54.98
And it's all valid.

1693
02:14:54.98 --> 02:14:55.82
It's all valid.

1694
02:14:55.82 --> 02:14:57.38
It's almost all valid, I should say.

1695
02:14:57.38 --> 02:15:02.78
And it's you who's the mediator of all this pressure

1696
02:15:02.78 --> 02:15:05.38
from higher and the bubbling up from your sport.

1697
02:15:05.38 --> 02:15:07.58
Plus you've got some stuff going on in your own life.

1698
02:15:07.58 --> 02:15:09.30
You're trying to get back with your girlfriend,

1699
02:15:09.30 --> 02:15:11.70
your best friends, getting killed or injured.

1700
02:15:11.70 --> 02:15:13.30
And so you've got your own.

1701
02:15:13.30 --> 02:15:18.98
And you've got to be this person, this intermediary

1702
02:15:18.98 --> 02:15:20.46
in between all that.

1703
