But we'll get into some of that.

1954
02:26:22.74 --> 02:26:27.42
But it's you at this juncture returning home.

1955
02:26:27.42 --> 02:26:30.38
I'm going to go to the book.

1956
02:26:30.38 --> 02:26:35.38
On April 20, 2011, I landed back on US soil.

1957
02:26:35.38 --> 02:26:37.18
I was 25 years old.

1958
02:26:37.18 --> 02:26:40.58
Had had just lived a lifetime on fast forward.

1959
02:26:40.58 --> 02:26:42.14
My body was battered.

1960
02:26:42.14 --> 02:26:45.30
And my brain was traumatized by multiple blasts,

1961
02:26:45.30 --> 02:26:48.10
the type of injuries sustained by so many of us

1962
02:26:48.10 --> 02:26:51.06
in the post-911 wars.

1963
02:26:51.06 --> 02:26:53.86
But I also came home from Sangen, exhausted,

1964
02:26:53.86 --> 02:26:58.90
embittered, angry, and unsure how to express any of it.

1965
02:26:58.90 --> 02:27:01.58
There was no way to physically represent the moral injuries

1966
02:27:01.58 --> 02:27:02.74
I had sustained.

1967
02:27:02.74 --> 02:27:06.06
And I did not know a way to talk about them,

1968
02:27:06.06 --> 02:27:08.78
though they were evident to anyone who knew me.

1969
02:27:08.78 --> 02:27:12.34
I was still angry at what I had felt had been

1970
02:27:12.34 --> 02:27:15.22
Kilo Company headquarters punishing me for aggressively

1971
02:27:15.22 --> 02:27:17.70
implementing orders I was given.

1972
02:27:17.70 --> 02:27:21.62
I was depressed by the death and injury of my friends.

1973
02:27:21.62 --> 02:27:25.50
I was physically rung out from seven months of insomnia,

1974
02:27:25.50 --> 02:27:29.42
long daily movements under load, and the accumulated stress

1975
02:27:29.42 --> 02:27:31.74
of leading young men in a place where someone

1976
02:27:31.74 --> 02:27:35.78
was trying to kill all of us every day.

1977
02:27:35.78 --> 02:27:40.14
Strangely, like an addict having withdrawals,

1978
02:27:40.14 --> 02:27:42.62
I still missed the almost daily combat

1979
02:27:42.62 --> 02:27:46.02
for the first four months of our deployment.

1980
02:27:46.02 --> 02:27:50.38
Worse yet, just as an IED does invisible damage to Marines,

1981
02:27:50.38 --> 02:27:54.78
as its shockwave passes through their soft internal organs,

1982
02:27:54.78 --> 02:27:58.26
people in my orbit were suffering from my injuries.

1983
02:27:58.26 --> 02:28:00.46
In the week before we got back, my mom

1984
02:28:00.46 --> 02:28:03.42
was counting the hours through sleepless nights

1985
02:28:03.42 --> 02:28:05.66
at work or inability to stop crying

1986
02:28:05.66 --> 02:28:06.70
in a bathroom.

1987
02:28:06.70 --> 02:28:10.30
Stahl got her sent home for the day to recover.

1988
02:28:10.30 --> 02:28:16.34
When she met me in Southern California on return,

1989
02:28:16.34 --> 02:28:19.74
she tried to talk to me about how I was feeling.

1990
02:28:19.74 --> 02:28:21.34
I didn't want to talk about it.

1991
02:28:21.34 --> 02:28:23.38
My desire not to talk never really

1992
02:28:23.38 --> 02:28:25.46
mattered where my mom is concerned, especially

1993
02:28:25.46 --> 02:28:30.54
after she took it upon herself to read my journal from Sangen.

1994
02:28:30.54 --> 02:28:32.98
I was angry at the violation of my privacy.

1995
02:28:32.98 --> 02:28:35.90
Thomas, I can't understand what happened over there

1996
02:28:35.90 --> 02:28:37.46
because you won't talk about it.

1997
02:28:37.46 --> 02:28:39.14
Mom, I'm fine.

1998
02:28:39.14 --> 02:28:42.58
Then please make eye contact with me when I'm talking to you.

1999
02:28:42.58 --> 02:28:44.22
Would you just let it go?

2000
02:28:44.22 --> 02:28:46.42
Thomas, you're my son and my best friend.

2001
02:28:46.42 --> 02:28:49.02
You have been since you were born.

2002
02:28:49.02 --> 02:28:50.82
It's like you're not there anymore.

2003
02:28:50.82 --> 02:28:53.66
You're just this angry person and I'm on eggshells.

2004
02:28:53.66 --> 02:28:56.78
I'm not letting anything go.

2005
02:28:56.78 --> 02:28:58.50
What do you want to say to me, mom?

2006
02:28:58.50 --> 02:29:03.26
I said, I'm fine.

2007
02:29:03.26 --> 02:29:09.38
So doing just fine, huh?

2008
02:29:09.38 --> 02:29:11.74
You weren't exactly fine.

2009
02:29:11.74 --> 02:29:15.38
A lot of stuff going on in the head.

2010
02:29:15.38 --> 02:29:20.82
Yeah, undoubtedly, there are tons of benefits

2011
02:29:20.82 --> 02:29:22.58
of those experiences.

2012
02:29:22.58 --> 02:29:25.46
At that time, still a little bit raw.

2013
02:29:25.46 --> 02:29:30.58
I think ultimately we get to post-traumatic growth.

2014
02:29:30.58 --> 02:29:33.86
But before you can get to post-traumatic growth,

2015
02:29:33.86 --> 02:29:35.66
you've got to get to gratitude and you've

2016
02:29:35.66 --> 02:29:39.62
got to find a way to be thankful for that adversity,

2017
02:29:39.62 --> 02:29:40.70
thankful for that hardship.

2018
02:29:40.70 --> 02:29:42.82
You've got to get to your good.

2019
02:29:42.82 --> 02:29:49.94
And initially, when those tough things happen,

2020
02:29:49.94 --> 02:29:54.38
you don't say, oh, I'm so happy that this tough thing happened.

2021
02:29:54.38 --> 02:29:55.86
Whether it's a car accident or cancer,

2022
02:29:55.86 --> 02:29:57.50
you don't say, I'm so happy.

2023
02:29:57.50 --> 02:30:00.82
But the thing happened.

2024
02:30:00.82 --> 02:30:03.02
And so at some point, you can either

2025
02:30:03.02 --> 02:30:05.46
continue to be a victim of that thing

2026
02:30:05.46 --> 02:30:09.58
or you can take your agency back and say good.

2027
02:30:09.58 --> 02:30:12.74
And when you do that, you can say,

2028
02:30:12.74 --> 02:30:14.86
I am thankful for the things that I've

2029
02:30:14.86 --> 02:30:17.18
learned from having this experience.

2030
02:30:17.18 --> 02:30:20.94
And that's why I know many amputees and lots of,

2031
02:30:20.94 --> 02:30:23.38
and this is the cycle.

2032
02:30:23.38 --> 02:30:26.98
Initially, bitter, angry.

2033
02:30:26.98 --> 02:30:29.10
But even the double amputee, triple amputee,

2034
02:30:29.10 --> 02:30:31.66
these guys I know, they'll finally get to a place

2035
02:30:31.66 --> 02:30:35.18
where they say, I wouldn't trade that experience

2036
02:30:35.18 --> 02:30:37.66
because of the things that I've learned and been and fitted

2037
02:30:37.66 --> 02:30:40.70
from and the man that I am today because of that.

2038
02:30:40.70 --> 02:30:43.10
And so you get to gratitude and then you finally

2039
02:30:43.10 --> 02:30:44.30
can get to that growth.

2040
02:30:44.30 --> 02:30:49.94
But undoubtedly, in this moment, I'm still very hurt

2041
02:30:49.94 --> 02:30:51.38
and offended.

2042
02:30:51.38 --> 02:30:52.38
I don't know, offended.

2043
02:30:52.38 --> 02:30:57.26
Again, there was felt like some betrayal, do this thing.

2044
02:30:57.26 --> 02:31:01.26
But then I'd come back in and be like, why are your hands

2045
02:31:01.26 --> 02:31:02.50
bloody?

2046
02:31:02.50 --> 02:31:05.26
Why you got a lot?

2047
02:31:05.26 --> 02:31:08.86
You kind of seems pretty messy out there.

2048
02:31:08.86 --> 02:31:11.42
Yeah, you go out there and tell everybody,

2049
02:31:11.42 --> 02:31:13.18
we go kill these guys, go do this thing.

2050
02:31:13.18 --> 02:31:15.50
And then when the generals come, we're like, hey,

2051
02:31:15.50 --> 02:31:18.06
sledgehammer kills everybody.

2052
02:31:18.06 --> 02:31:20.82
And then you call me in and say, oh,

2053
02:31:20.82 --> 02:31:24.46
well, are you sure that guy had a gun?

2054
02:31:24.46 --> 02:31:27.30
Yes, what are you implying, sir?

2055
02:31:27.30 --> 02:31:33.54
And so it's just carrying too much weight already

2056
02:31:33.54 --> 02:31:37.50
to have, did not feel like your chain of command

2057
02:31:37.50 --> 02:31:39.10
has your back.

2058
02:31:39.10 --> 02:31:42.30
And there were times within the company

2059
02:31:42.30 --> 02:31:44.86
where I felt extremely betrayed.

2060
02:31:44.86 --> 02:31:51.38
And so yeah, I think I was dealing with that.

2061
02:31:51.38 --> 02:31:54.38
Ultimately, though, I think I was

2062
02:31:54.38 --> 02:32:00.14
thankful to have porcelain toilets, California

2063
02:32:00.14 --> 02:32:03.90
burritos, pretty girlfriend.

2064
02:32:03.90 --> 02:32:05.62
San Clemente doesn't suck.

2065
02:32:05.62 --> 02:32:09.78
So a lot of things to be thankful for at that time as well,

2066
02:32:09.78 --> 02:32:12.78
but still trying to figure some things out

2067
02:32:12.78 --> 02:32:15.02
and maybe not doing it that well.

2068
02:32:18.30 --> 02:32:21.82
What was your enlistment status at this point?

2069
02:32:21.82 --> 02:32:22.94
Like, where were you at?

2070
02:32:22.94 --> 02:32:26.02
Did you come back thinking maybe you'll get out?

2071
02:32:26.02 --> 02:32:28.90
Did you come back thinking I'm definitely staying in?

2072
02:32:28.90 --> 02:32:30.54
No, I thought I was going to get out.

2073
02:32:30.54 --> 02:32:36.58
I mean, I didn't have this lifelong desire to serve.

2074
02:32:36.58 --> 02:32:38.14
I didn't grow up as a kid thinking, oh,

2075
02:32:38.14 --> 02:32:39.62
I want to be a soldier someday.

2076
02:32:39.62 --> 02:32:45.26
And I never thought, oh, I want to be a general or a colonel

2077
02:32:45.26 --> 02:32:47.30
or any of this kind of stuff.

2078
02:32:47.30 --> 02:32:49.86
I thought I should do something.

2079
02:32:49.86 --> 02:32:51.66
And then I thought I should be a Marine.

2080
02:32:51.66 --> 02:32:52.98
I thought I should be an infantry Marine.

2081
02:32:52.98 --> 02:32:54.86
And then once I finally figured out, yes,

2082
02:32:54.86 --> 02:32:57.70
I should be an infantry Marine, I thought I should fight.

2083
02:32:57.70 --> 02:32:58.78
And I did that.

2084
02:32:58.78 --> 02:33:01.78
And I got to lead the best men in this nation.

2085
02:33:01.78 --> 02:33:04.82
And so I had met my career goals.

2086
02:33:04.82 --> 02:33:07.94
And then with the amount of crap that I had experienced,

2087
02:33:07.94 --> 02:33:10.34
I said, maybe I'm out.

2088
02:33:10.34 --> 02:33:12.34
And so there's this thing called career designation

2089
02:33:12.34 --> 02:33:13.82
that you're offered as a lieutenant.

2090
02:33:13.82 --> 02:33:14.82
And you've got to accept it.

2091
02:33:14.82 --> 02:33:19.78
And I was not going to designate because I was really

2092
02:33:19.78 --> 02:33:24.66
disenchanted or just disappointed with some

2093
02:33:24.66 --> 02:33:25.78
of that company leadership.

2094
02:33:25.78 --> 02:33:27.90
And so I was going to get out.

2095
02:33:27.90 --> 02:33:31.06
I was serving as an Exo and an adjacent company.

2096
02:33:31.06 --> 02:33:31.54
So from this.

2097
02:33:31.54 --> 02:33:33.06
Is this when you went to Lima Company?

2098
02:33:33.06 --> 02:33:34.54
Yeah.

2099
02:33:34.54 --> 02:33:36.86
You know the frustration that you're talking about,

2100
02:33:36.86 --> 02:33:38.46
with the leadership, right?

2101
02:33:38.46 --> 02:33:39.66
How did you work through that?

2102
02:33:42.58 --> 02:33:46.98
During the deployment, not well.

2103
02:33:46.98 --> 02:33:49.10
I mean, between my company, Gunny,

2104
02:33:49.10 --> 02:33:51.34
who ended up getting medivac'd and Zach,

2105
02:33:51.34 --> 02:33:54.66
I would say there were times where I was on the verge

2106
02:33:54.66 --> 02:33:56.18
of a nervous breakdown.

2107
02:33:56.18 --> 02:33:58.34
It was never the Taliban.

2108
02:33:58.34 --> 02:34:03.54
It was like, I've been training to shoot silhouettes of men

2109
02:34:03.54 --> 02:34:04.62
for years.

2110
02:34:04.62 --> 02:34:06.10
And now I'm shooting.

2111
02:34:06.10 --> 02:34:11.02
And so I am only happy when a Taliban is dead.

2112
02:34:11.02 --> 02:34:13.42
That is no problem.

2113
02:34:13.42 --> 02:34:17.18
And I also am not personally offended that the Taliban is

2114
02:34:17.18 --> 02:34:17.82
shooting at me.

2115
02:34:17.82 --> 02:34:19.74
I know that that's what the Taliban does.

2116
02:34:19.74 --> 02:34:20.70
They shoot at us.

2117
02:34:20.70 --> 02:34:25.14
And so I've been training for that.

2118
02:34:25.14 --> 02:34:26.86
Contact front, contact left.

2119
02:34:26.86 --> 02:34:29.18
I'm training to be shot at.

2120
02:34:29.18 --> 02:34:32.50
And then Marines get wounded.

2121
02:34:32.50 --> 02:34:34.86
Well, why do we have the tourniquets on?

2122
02:34:34.86 --> 02:34:35.86
Why do we do tourniquet drills?

2123
02:34:35.86 --> 02:34:37.90
Why are we doing all these combat lifesaver?

2124
02:34:37.90 --> 02:34:41.94
And it's all these things you expect.

2125
02:34:41.94 --> 02:34:43.86
And if you're paying attention and taking your training

2126
02:34:43.86 --> 02:34:46.14
seriously, you expect that there will be casualties,

2127
02:34:46.14 --> 02:34:48.06
that you will have to kill people, that you will see.

2128
02:34:48.06 --> 02:34:50.58
And so all of that was OK.

2129
02:34:50.58 --> 02:34:53.70
And when you go outside the wire, you're in the yellow.

2130
02:34:53.70 --> 02:34:55.02
You're alert.

2131
02:34:55.02 --> 02:34:56.10
You're scanning your baseline.

2132
02:34:56.10 --> 02:34:57.10
You're waiting for that.

2133
02:34:57.10 --> 02:34:59.54
And so when you're in the yellow and you're alert,

2134
02:34:59.54 --> 02:35:03.34
you can respond to things fluidly, adaptively.

2135
02:35:03.34 --> 02:35:05.70
But you leave the wire at condition one.

2136
02:35:05.70 --> 02:35:08.86
You leave the wire in full PP, flat, gavelar,

2137
02:35:08.86 --> 02:35:11.78
because you know you're going into a hostile environment.

2138
02:35:11.78 --> 02:35:15.22
When you come back inside the wire, condition four,

2139
02:35:15.22 --> 02:35:17.86
take your flak off, because now you're

2140
02:35:17.86 --> 02:35:20.22
within friendly lines.

2141
02:35:20.22 --> 02:35:24.10
And when you get ambushed within friendly lines,

2142
02:35:24.10 --> 02:35:25.62
that's where you're vulnerable.

2143
02:35:25.62 --> 02:35:27.34
And that's when you can really get hurt.

2144
02:35:27.34 --> 02:35:30.78
And those moral injuries, I think, often

2145
02:35:30.78 --> 02:35:36.54
not last the pain associated with physical injuries.

2146
02:35:36.54 --> 02:35:40.78
And so what I did when I got back to the States

2147
02:35:40.78 --> 02:35:42.42
is I just ran.

2148
02:35:42.42 --> 02:35:44.42
I ran and ran and ran.

2149
02:35:44.42 --> 02:35:47.38
And those fire breaks outside Camp Pellenton,

2150
02:35:47.38 --> 02:35:51.70
every morning I would just go run for as long as I could,

2151
02:35:51.70 --> 02:35:53.86
for as far as I could.

2152
02:35:53.86 --> 02:35:56.98
And then I would just pour myself into my work,

2153
02:35:56.98 --> 02:36:01.10
as I was dealing with things.

2154
02:36:01.10 --> 02:36:05.06
How did you come to the conclusion that you would stay in?

2155
02:36:05.06 --> 02:36:06.30
I had a new boss.

2156
02:36:06.30 --> 02:36:10.02
And the new Lima Company commander came in.

2157
02:36:10.02 --> 02:36:12.58
He's my current boss.

2158
02:36:12.58 --> 02:36:16.82
And he was everything I'd hoped for.

2159
02:36:16.82 --> 02:36:20.50
He was IOC instructors, had such high standards.

2160
02:36:20.50 --> 02:36:21.62
And they were so challenging.

2161
02:36:21.62 --> 02:36:23.22
They were so good.

2162
02:36:23.22 --> 02:36:26.82
And I was like, man, a Marine captain, that's something.

2163
02:36:26.82 --> 02:36:28.06
That is a Marine captain.

2164
02:36:28.06 --> 02:36:29.10
That is really something.

2165
02:36:29.10 --> 02:36:34.06
And then I found myself disappointed throughout my work

2166
02:36:34.06 --> 02:36:37.26
up and deployment and disillusioned.

2167
02:36:37.26 --> 02:36:41.14
And then this, and so I'm thinking I'm out.

2168
02:36:41.14 --> 02:36:44.02
I'll go back to Chicago, going to be a fireman,

2169
02:36:44.02 --> 02:36:46.82
took the fireman test.

2170
02:36:46.82 --> 02:36:49.22
Then this guy came in.

2171
02:36:49.22 --> 02:36:51.42
And we want to be Marines because we

2172
02:36:51.42 --> 02:36:52.46
want to do hard shit.

2173
02:36:52.46 --> 02:36:54.42
We want to be challenged.

2174
02:36:54.42 --> 02:36:56.70
I wanted to be a Marine because they had higher standards.

2175
02:36:56.70 --> 02:36:58.50
I looked at them and thought it's high standards.

2176
02:36:58.50 --> 02:36:59.74
That's what I want.

2177
02:36:59.74 --> 02:37:02.42
And this guy came in and he emulated all those high

2178
02:37:02.42 --> 02:37:02.94
standards.

2179
02:37:02.94 --> 02:37:05.38
And every day, I had to be at the top of my game.

2180
02:37:05.38 --> 02:37:07.54
Every day, I had to get better.

2181
02:37:07.54 --> 02:37:09.50
And that's all I want.

2182
02:37:09.50 --> 02:37:14.18
A leader who emulated what he espoused,

2183
02:37:14.18 --> 02:37:18.26
a leader who was accountable and who held me accountable.

2184
02:37:18.26 --> 02:37:23.50
As a lieutenant, I had very little oversight, which

2185
02:37:23.50 --> 02:37:24.82
in some ways was awesome.

2186
02:37:24.82 --> 02:37:27.10
Because I just got to go running gun all the time out

2187
02:37:27.10 --> 02:37:28.26
and doing my thing.

2188
02:37:28.26 --> 02:37:29.90
But I needed somebody to mentor me.

2189
02:37:29.90 --> 02:37:31.66
I needed someone to hold me more accountable.

2190
02:37:31.66 --> 02:37:35.58
I needed someone to develop me and coach me and teach me.

2191
02:37:35.58 --> 02:37:36.62
And he did those things.

2192
02:37:36.62 --> 02:37:42.14
And I said, OK, well, I want to do this, what he's doing

2193
02:37:42.14 --> 02:37:42.94
for somebody someday.

2194
02:37:42.94 --> 02:37:44.82
And so I said, I'm going to stay in.

2195
02:37:44.82 --> 02:37:49.42
But as we grinded towards the Mew,

2196
02:37:49.42 --> 02:37:51.82
I saw a flyer at the gym that said,

2197
02:37:51.82 --> 02:37:55.02
do you have what it takes, come try out for recon.

2198
02:37:55.02 --> 02:37:58.18
And I said, yeah, maybe this XO staff life isn't for me.

2199
02:37:58.18 --> 02:38:01.14
I'm going to try to go fight again with some troops.

2200
02:38:01.14 --> 02:38:07.46
Yeah, I guess no matter what industry you're in,

2201
02:38:07.46 --> 02:38:14.06
whether you're in the Marine Corps, Army, IBM,

2202
02:38:14.06 --> 02:38:16.02
you name the company, you're going

2203
02:38:16.02 --> 02:38:17.82
to have some good bosses.

2204
02:38:17.82 --> 02:38:19.50
You're going to have some bad bosses.

2205
02:38:19.50 --> 02:38:22.38
And a lot of it has to do with what I was talking about

2206
02:38:22.38 --> 02:38:24.70
earlier, like if you're not doing your best

2207
02:38:24.70 --> 02:38:27.22
to understand the perspective of the person above you

2208
02:38:27.22 --> 02:38:30.10
and the chain of command, it's going to be hard.

2209
02:38:30.10 --> 02:38:31.02
And here's the thing.

2210
02:38:31.02 --> 02:38:34.42
There's at least a 50% chance that they're not

2211
02:38:34.42 --> 02:38:36.14
trying to understand your perspective at all.

2212
02:38:36.14 --> 02:38:38.30
There's a 50% chance that they just

2213
02:38:38.30 --> 02:38:41.98
think you should just be conforming to what I'm telling

2214
02:38:41.98 --> 02:38:44.38
you and complying with what I tell you.

2215
02:38:44.38 --> 02:38:46.94
There's a 50% chance you got a boss like that.

2216
02:38:46.94 --> 02:38:50.38
And in that case, you can sit there and be mad like,

2217
02:38:50.38 --> 02:38:51.78
why don't they understand?

2218
02:38:51.78 --> 02:38:53.54
Or you can say, OK, I got to work with this.

2219
02:38:53.54 --> 02:38:57.06
I got to make sure I do my best to make them understand.

2220
02:38:57.06 --> 02:38:59.02
I got to paint a better picture.

2221
02:38:59.02 --> 02:39:01.06
I've got to do a better job.

2222
02:39:01.06 --> 02:39:03.54
And again, it goes back to that gives you

2223
02:39:03.54 --> 02:39:08.66
some kind of agency over your life to think, OK,

2224
02:39:08.66 --> 02:39:10.42
my boss is an egomaniac.

2225
02:39:10.42 --> 02:39:11.86
My boss has a bad temper.

2226
02:39:11.86 --> 02:39:15.06
My boss doesn't understand my perspective.

2227
02:39:15.06 --> 02:39:17.90
My boss is looking to get promoted,

2228
02:39:17.90 --> 02:39:19.22
and that's the main thing he's felt.

2229
02:39:19.22 --> 02:39:21.50
Like all those things, all those horrible things.

2230
02:39:21.50 --> 02:39:23.46
And we all work for people like that.

2231
02:39:23.46 --> 02:39:24.50
And you go, OK, cool.

2232
02:39:24.50 --> 02:39:25.38
That's what my boss is like.

2233
02:39:25.38 --> 02:39:26.74
All right, here's what I'm going to do.

2234
02:39:26.74 --> 02:39:28.94
Here's how I'm going to build a relationship with my boss.

2235
02:39:28.94 --> 02:39:30.62
Here's how I'm going to build trust with my boss,

2236
02:39:30.62 --> 02:39:32.58
regardless of what their situation is.

2237
02:39:32.58 --> 02:39:35.38
So I'm just saying, I like the fact

2238
02:39:35.38 --> 02:39:39.90
that you were able to get to a point where you say, OK,

2239
02:39:39.90 --> 02:39:40.74
there's good bosses.

2240
02:39:40.74 --> 02:39:42.74
There's bad bosses out there.

2241
02:39:42.74 --> 02:39:43.86
Of course, everybody.

2242
02:39:43.86 --> 02:39:45.38
Try and be a good boss.

2243
02:39:45.38 --> 02:39:46.94
Try and support the people in the field.

2244
02:39:46.94 --> 02:39:48.34
That's 100% it.

2245
02:39:48.34 --> 02:39:52.18
But when you're a subordinate and your boss is maybe not

2246
02:39:52.18 --> 02:39:55.34
quite what you dreamed of, good challenge.

2247
02:39:55.34 --> 02:39:57.62
Build a good relationship with them.

2248
02:39:57.62 --> 02:40:00.94
And things are going to get better.

2249
02:40:00.94 --> 02:40:03.86
That's the way it works.

2250
02:40:03.86 --> 02:40:06.74
In the meantime, you get married, right?

2251
02:40:06.74 --> 02:40:08.74
You make that decision.

2252
02:40:08.74 --> 02:40:11.06
You finally say, all right, I'm going to do this.

2253
02:40:11.06 --> 02:40:14.06
Is that before you screened for recon?

2254
02:40:14.06 --> 02:40:15.18
It was before I screened.

2255
02:40:15.18 --> 02:40:16.74
It was right when I got back.

2256
02:40:16.74 --> 02:40:17.98
Right when you got back?

2257
02:40:17.98 --> 02:40:18.54
You closed the deal.

2258
02:40:18.54 --> 02:40:19.42
Court wedding.

2259
02:40:19.42 --> 02:40:20.54
Yeah.

2260
02:40:20.54 --> 02:40:23.50
She put up with me dumping her right before I left.

2261
02:40:23.50 --> 02:40:25.94
And then all my sad phone calls, and I never get the sad phone.

2262
02:40:25.94 --> 02:40:28.02
I said, you better go do the right thing.

2263
02:40:28.02 --> 02:40:30.90
And so I did a court wedding a couple of weeks

2264
02:40:30.90 --> 02:40:32.06
after I got back.

2265
02:40:32.06 --> 02:40:33.90
And then you go to recon.

2266
02:40:33.90 --> 02:40:36.42
And you got some cool, you had an interesting day

2267
02:40:36.42 --> 02:40:40.66
of getting selected for recon, which was actually

2268
02:40:40.66 --> 02:40:41.46
a pretty cool story.

2269
02:40:41.46 --> 02:40:42.42
We won't go into it now.

2270
02:40:42.42 --> 02:40:44.74
People can read the book for that one.

2271
02:40:44.74 --> 02:40:47.54
But you end up getting selected for recon.

2272
02:40:47.54 --> 02:40:49.02
But do I have this right?

2273
02:40:49.02 --> 02:40:52.42
Instead of going to reconnaissance school,

2274
02:40:52.42 --> 02:40:55.98
they have recon on deployment or going on deployment quickly.

2275
02:40:55.98 --> 02:40:57.70
And they say, hey, you're not going to recon school.

2276
02:40:57.70 --> 02:40:59.42
You're going to go be an advisor.

2277
02:40:59.42 --> 02:41:01.46
So the battalion was deployed.

2278
02:41:01.46 --> 02:41:03.22
So when I showed up, the battalion was deployed.

2279
02:41:03.22 --> 02:41:06.30
I'm the one guy back, a couple guys back.

2280
02:41:06.30 --> 02:41:08.70
And I was supposed to go to school.

2281
02:41:08.70 --> 02:41:11.10
And then it's called an IA, and an individual augment

2282
02:41:11.10 --> 02:41:11.66
came down.

2283
02:41:11.66 --> 02:41:14.66
And they said, hey, we need one dude

2284
02:41:14.66 --> 02:41:18.34
to go advise the Afghan on how to be recon.

2285
02:41:18.34 --> 02:41:19.70
You're all we got.

2286
02:41:19.70 --> 02:41:21.14
Even though you haven't been to school,

2287
02:41:21.14 --> 02:41:23.82
you're going to go advise these guys how to be.

2288
02:41:23.82 --> 02:41:25.58
And so I joined an advisor team that

2289
02:41:25.58 --> 02:41:28.98
was mostly guys, senior officers who

2290
02:41:28.98 --> 02:41:33.94
were going to advise a brigade level, so like staff stuff.

2291
02:41:33.94 --> 02:41:36.86
And me and a recon staff sergeant

2292
02:41:36.86 --> 02:41:41.02
were going to go out and advise the Afghan recon company.

2293
02:41:41.02 --> 02:41:44.54
So you've been back home for how long at this point?

2294
02:41:44.54 --> 02:41:47.70
I was home probably for about five or six months

2295
02:41:47.70 --> 02:41:50.34
when I got the word that I was going

2296
02:41:50.34 --> 02:41:52.30
to get the individual augment.

2297
02:41:52.30 --> 02:41:56.62
And then July 2012, you go back to Afghanistan.

2298
02:41:56.62 --> 02:41:58.94
You're out at patrol base Long Beach.

2299
02:41:58.94 --> 02:42:00.46
What was that setup like?

2300
02:42:00.46 --> 02:42:01.94
It was an old artillery firing position.

2301
02:42:01.94 --> 02:42:05.34
It was just a triangle, tiny, tiny little firing base

2302
02:42:05.34 --> 02:42:07.42
outside of Marja.

2303
02:42:07.42 --> 02:42:09.34
And it was July.

2304
02:42:09.34 --> 02:42:13.26
And the human factors, like the human factors

2305
02:42:13.26 --> 02:42:16.18
of the first deployment was the losing the guys

2306
02:42:16.18 --> 02:42:18.86
and the fighting and the grinding every day.

2307
02:42:18.86 --> 02:42:22.58
This was, I mean, not that I had any amenities really

2308
02:42:22.58 --> 02:42:24.82
on that first deployment, but this deployment,

2309
02:42:24.82 --> 02:42:27.50
I mean, it was a cot, a camionette, a pallet of water,

2310
02:42:27.50 --> 02:42:28.98
and a pallet of MREs.

2311
02:42:28.98 --> 02:42:29.86
And that's it.

2312
02:42:29.86 --> 02:42:32.02
And I was living with the ANA.

2313
02:42:32.02 --> 02:42:34.98
Right downwind from the shitter.

2314
02:42:34.98 --> 02:42:38.46
It was like the plagues of Moses coming through that place,

2315
02:42:38.46 --> 02:42:42.58
like bugs coming through and waves blocking out the sun.

2316
02:42:42.58 --> 02:42:47.58
I mean, it was hard, hard living out there in July.

2317
02:42:48.26 --> 02:42:50.58
And then, yeah, I'm going out, I'm fighting with the ANA

2318
02:42:50.58 --> 02:42:52.30
and then I'm a JTAC.

2319
02:42:52.30 --> 02:42:54.50
So I'm like a freelance JTAC.

2320
02:42:54.50 --> 02:42:58.06
So anybody who needs the guy for an op, they're calling me

2321
02:42:58.06 --> 02:43:00.38
and I'm getting to go on some pretty cool ops.

2322
02:43:00.38 --> 02:43:02.34
How many ANA are you out there with?

2323
02:43:02.34 --> 02:43:04.10
About 50.

2324
02:43:04.10 --> 02:43:07.14
So it's you, how many American advisors?

2325
02:43:07.14 --> 02:43:09.14
The one other Staff Sergeant counterpart

2326
02:43:09.14 --> 02:43:11.90
and then we'd pull like four or five grunts

2327
02:43:11.90 --> 02:43:15.58
from the AEO who would kind of help stand security.

2328
02:43:17.38 --> 02:43:18.30
So it was very lonely.

2329
02:43:18.30 --> 02:43:20.98
So this is a totally different kind of deployment.

2330
02:43:20.98 --> 02:43:23.22
Again, the disparity of different types of deployment

2331
02:43:23.22 --> 02:43:24.90
you can go on is insane.

2332
02:43:24.90 --> 02:43:27.42
For you to be out in the middle of nowhere now

2333
02:43:27.42 --> 02:43:30.02
with a bunch of freaking Afghans.

2334
02:43:30.02 --> 02:43:33.36
God.

2335
02:43:34.66 --> 02:43:37.78
Did you, so was your mission just to train these guys up?

2336
02:43:37.78 --> 02:43:41.86
Yeah, train the Afghan and partner, advise, assist

2337
02:43:41.86 --> 02:43:44.06
and then go out with them on operations.

2338
02:43:44.06 --> 02:43:46.14
And yeah, it was, but I mean, at this point

2339
02:43:46.14 --> 02:43:48.86
those guys have been trained for a really long time.

2340
02:43:48.86 --> 02:43:53.18
So I mean, really I'm just kind of talking to their leadership

2341
02:43:53.18 --> 02:43:55.50
and then going out on operations with them.

2342
02:43:55.50 --> 02:43:56.50
What's the op-temple like?

2343
02:43:56.50 --> 02:43:57.66
How often are you guys going out?

2344
02:43:57.66 --> 02:43:59.18
We're going out every day,

2345
02:43:59.18 --> 02:44:01.26
but it's not reconnaissance type missions.

2346
02:44:01.26 --> 02:44:03.94
It's like they're just basically better infantrymen

2347
02:44:03.94 --> 02:44:05.66
than your average Afghan soldier.

2348
02:44:05.66 --> 02:44:10.90
And so, but we really patrolled from like two a.m. to six a.m.

2349
02:44:10.90 --> 02:44:13.34
because by, you know, when the sun came up

2350
02:44:13.34 --> 02:44:14.70
it was over a hundred degrees.

2351
02:44:14.70 --> 02:44:15.82
And so for the first couple of months

2352
02:44:15.82 --> 02:44:18.50
it was just real early morning patrols,

2353
02:44:18.50 --> 02:44:21.74
not too kinetic with those guys.

2354
02:44:21.74 --> 02:44:24.62
But again, a company going out would say,

2355
02:44:24.62 --> 02:44:27.54
oh, we can have a JTAC just jump on this op.

2356
02:44:27.54 --> 02:44:29.06
And so when I was jumping on these ops

2357
02:44:29.06 --> 02:44:30.34
with the different Marine companies

2358
02:44:30.34 --> 02:44:33.18
we were getting it really getting into it.

2359
02:44:33.18 --> 02:44:36.58
Freelance JTAC in Afghanistan.

2360
02:44:36.58 --> 02:44:38.94
What'd you take away from a leadership perspective

2361
02:44:38.94 --> 02:44:40.86
on this deployment?

2362
02:44:40.86 --> 02:44:44.54
Leadership is lonely, which I've kind of already knew,

2363
02:44:44.54 --> 02:44:48.26
but it was particularly lonely when it's, you know,

2364
02:44:48.26 --> 02:44:50.26
couple of Lance Corporals

2365
02:44:50.26 --> 02:44:52.26
are the only other Americans around.

2366
02:44:52.26 --> 02:44:56.58
And so you could only talk about the things

2367
02:44:56.58 --> 02:44:59.66
that Lance Corporals talk about for so long.

2368
02:44:59.66 --> 02:45:04.66
And so that was really a lot of time to think by myself.

2369
02:45:09.66 --> 02:45:11.74
One of the things that I'm advising these guys

2370
02:45:11.74 --> 02:45:14.34
and one of them turns me and says,

2371
02:45:14.34 --> 02:45:16.50
well, you know when you leave is the Taliban

2372
02:45:16.50 --> 02:45:19.14
is just gonna take Afghanistan back anyways.

2373
02:45:19.14 --> 02:45:21.50
And I'm like, what are you talking about?

2374
02:45:21.50 --> 02:45:22.66
You got a whole army.

2375
02:45:22.66 --> 02:45:24.18
You got 10 years of training.

2376
02:45:24.18 --> 02:45:28.26
You got millions and I was like,

2377
02:45:28.26 --> 02:45:33.26
I want Afghanistan more than you want Afghanistan.

2378
02:45:33.26 --> 02:45:35.58
And it was a really important lesson for me

2379
02:45:35.58 --> 02:45:37.98
that you can't want something more for someone

2380
02:45:37.98 --> 02:45:39.18
than they want it for themselves.

2381
02:45:39.18 --> 02:45:43.42
And that applies to many different areas of life.

2382
02:45:43.42 --> 02:45:47.38
And so that was kind of hard to accept.

2383
02:45:47.38 --> 02:45:52.38
And I found that I am happiest when I'm under fire.

2384
02:45:55.22 --> 02:46:00.22
And like when you have a purpose

2385
02:46:00.88 --> 02:46:04.74
and that is being a warrior or combat leader

2386
02:46:04.74 --> 02:46:07.10
and you're good at that thing,

2387
02:46:07.10 --> 02:46:10.86
there is nothing more rewarding or satisfying

2388
02:46:10.86 --> 02:46:11.98
than when you get to,

2389
02:46:11.98 --> 02:46:14.78
and so got right back in the game

2390
02:46:14.78 --> 02:46:16.42
and right back in my first firefight,

2391
02:46:16.42 --> 02:46:18.26
I'm like, okay, here's what I don't do.

2392
02:46:18.26 --> 02:46:20.26
Like you're gonna do this, you're gonna do that.

2393
02:46:20.26 --> 02:46:24.90
And so, and then I was an enabler.

2394
02:46:24.90 --> 02:46:27.70
And that was a weird role for me

2395
02:46:27.70 --> 02:46:29.82
because I used to be in a commander.

2396
02:46:29.82 --> 02:46:31.50
And so when I'm the JTAC,

2397
02:46:31.50 --> 02:46:34.10
I don't have command of anybody.

2398
02:46:34.10 --> 02:46:36.02
I'm just there to support a commander.

2399
02:46:36.02 --> 02:46:39.90
And so it's tough because you see like,

2400
02:46:39.90 --> 02:46:42.50
here's what we need should be doing,

2401
02:46:42.50 --> 02:46:43.78
but like that's not your role.

2402
02:46:43.78 --> 02:46:47.30
So like staying in my role as an enabler

2403
02:46:47.30 --> 02:46:49.62
was different for me.

2404
02:46:49.62 --> 02:46:53.30
And so I got to appreciate maybe that role a little bit.

2405
02:46:56.94 --> 02:46:59.62
You get orders, go back to Pendleton.

2406
02:46:59.62 --> 02:47:01.70
It's now March, 2013.

2407
02:47:03.22 --> 02:47:07.54
When you get home, it's safe to say at this juncture,

2408
02:47:07.54 --> 02:47:12.18
your work-life balance was not in balance at all.

2409
02:47:12.18 --> 02:47:13.78
No, I just only did Marine stuff.

2410
02:47:15.62 --> 02:47:19.66
Andrea at this point, she had moved back to Chicago.

2411
02:47:19.66 --> 02:47:20.50
Yeah.

2412
02:47:22.70 --> 02:47:25.78
One of your buddies pulls you aside and is like,

2413
02:47:27.30 --> 02:47:29.14
do you want the Marine Corps or do you want marriage?

2414
02:47:29.14 --> 02:47:31.02
Like which one of these two things did you want?

2415
02:47:31.02 --> 02:47:33.58
Because they're mutually exclusive.

2416
02:47:33.58 --> 02:47:36.18
Like it doesn't sound like you'd be able to do both.

2417
02:47:37.90 --> 02:47:40.38
You decide marriage.

2418
02:47:40.38 --> 02:47:41.94
That's the thing you're gonna work towards.

2419
02:47:41.94 --> 02:47:44.42
And you tell your wife, I'll get out of the Marine Corps.

2420
02:47:44.42 --> 02:47:46.22
We can go home, we'll figure it out.

2421
02:47:48.02 --> 02:47:51.70
She says, nope, not it.

2422
02:47:51.70 --> 02:47:53.26
I still don't wanna be with you.

2423
02:47:55.46 --> 02:47:57.78
So this is a rough, this is rough.

2424
02:47:57.78 --> 02:48:00.14
Eventually you get her to come back.

2425
02:48:01.22 --> 02:48:03.94
She comes back out, back out here.

2426
02:48:03.94 --> 02:48:04.78
Yep.

2427
02:48:07.62 --> 02:48:10.90
Doesn't end up being, once again,

2428
02:48:10.90 --> 02:48:14.70
still not where it needs to be with her.

2429
02:48:14.70 --> 02:48:19.70
And you eventually find out that she'd been unfaithful to you

2430
02:48:20.58 --> 02:48:21.98
while you were on deployment.

2431
02:48:23.70 --> 02:48:26.34
With one of your fellow Marines.

2432
02:48:26.34 --> 02:48:31.34
With a Marine that live with you.

2433
02:48:31.34 --> 02:48:32.18
I'm not sure.

2434
02:48:40.30 --> 02:48:41.78
How do you get through that?

2435
02:48:43.66 --> 02:48:47.54
So I talk about ambushes, that life is full of ambushes.

2436
02:48:47.54 --> 02:48:52.54
And sometimes combat veterans will try to say like,

2437
02:48:53.62 --> 02:48:57.26
oh well, I was in an ambush with bullets and bombs.

2438
02:48:57.26 --> 02:49:01.10
And so you can, and I'll tell you that my worst ambush

2439
02:49:01.10 --> 02:49:03.54
was that was my worst ambush in my life.

2440
02:49:06.66 --> 02:49:09.14
So I try not to establish higher,

2441
02:49:09.14 --> 02:49:10.50
like everyone's trying to compete

2442
02:49:10.50 --> 02:49:12.30
and who had the worst or who,

2443
02:49:12.30 --> 02:49:15.86
and so combat veterans think that we have this,

2444
02:49:15.86 --> 02:49:19.50
or veterans in general think that we have this special kind of,

2445
02:49:19.50 --> 02:49:21.98
people should feel bad for us because we did this.

2446
02:49:21.98 --> 02:49:24.70
First off, I volunteered for those things.

2447
02:49:24.70 --> 02:49:25.66
I wanted those things.

2448
02:49:25.66 --> 02:49:26.62
I sought those things.

2449
02:49:26.62 --> 02:49:27.94
No one made me do that.

2450
02:49:27.94 --> 02:49:31.94
I was trained and prepared for those things.

2451
02:49:31.94 --> 02:49:35.58
I wasn't trained or prepared for that.

2452
02:49:39.70 --> 02:49:43.70
And that was a moral injury that took a long time,

2453
02:49:47.26 --> 02:49:51.46
and maybe still presently one that you heal from.

2454
02:49:51.46 --> 02:49:56.46
And much of my motivation in life is a response not to repeat

2455
02:50:00.06 --> 02:50:03.66
the same mistakes that I experienced when I was growing up.

2456
02:50:03.66 --> 02:50:05.70
And one of those was divorce.

2457
02:50:05.70 --> 02:50:07.02
And so I thought, no matter what,

2458
02:50:07.02 --> 02:50:08.64
I'm not gonna get divorced.

2459
02:50:08.64 --> 02:50:18.64
